<font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="4">Naomi Klein on capitalism and the free market</font><br>
<font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="5"><b>A system built on crisis and violence</b></font><p>
<font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2">December 14, 2007 | Pages 8 and 9</font><p>

<font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">NAOMI KLEIN'S new book <i><a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/redirect.html?ie=UTF8&amp;location=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2FShock-Doctrine-Rise-Disaster-Capitalism%2Fdp%2F0805079831%3Fie%3DUTF8%26s%3Dbooks%26qid%3D1197235238%26sr%3D8-1&amp;tag=socialistwork-20&amp;linkCode=ur2&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325" target="_blank">The Shock Doctrine</a> </i>is an indictment of capitalism and the free-market system in the era of neoliberalism and the "war on terror." During her tour to promote the book, she sat down with ANTHONY ARNOVE to talk about some of the themes she takes up in <i>The Shock Doctrine</i>, and the questions she's encountered at her appearances.<p>
<p><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="1">- - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -</font></p>

<font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>WHEN YOU look at how the disaster of the U.S. occupation of Iraq is portrayed these days, the emphasis now is always on the mistakes the Bush administration made and its incompetence in planning for the occupation. In <i>The Shock Doctrine</i> and your essay "Baghdad Year Zero," you paint a very different picture of the underlying reasons for the invasion and occupation. Why do you think that the framework of "mistakes" and "mismanagement" is still the primary way people analyze the war, despite the evidence?</b><p>

WHEN YOU push people about what they believe the broader mission is, they don't really have an answer, because all of the "official" stories have fallen away.<p>
Nobody really believes it's about "bringing democracy," and we know there were no WMDs and no 9/11 link. So the idea that economic ambitions for the region could have been an essential motivating force and the centerpiece of the postwar plan seems to be a logical conclusion to draw, based on the evidence we have.<p>
It's not a secret plan. So an effort has been made on the part of analysts to downplay this in the face of overwhelming evidence that this was a priority.<p>

<table width="270" align="right"><tr><td>
<table width="258" cellpadding="12" cellspacing="0" align="right" border="2" hspace="8" bordercolor="006699" bgcolor="#FFCC66"><tr><td>
<font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="4" color="#990000"><b>What else to read</b></font><p>
<font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2"><a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/redirect.html?ie=UTF8&amp;location=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2FShock-Doctrine-Rise-Disaster-Capitalism%2Fdp%2F0805079831%3Fie%3DUTF8%26s%3Dbooks%26qid%3D1197235238%26sr%3D8-1&amp;tag=socialistwork-20&amp;linkCode=ur2&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325" target="_blank"><i>The Shock Doctrine</i></a> by Naomi Klein argues that while people are reeling from natural disasters, wars and economic upheavals, politicians and industry leaders are implementing repressive policies designed to maximize their wealth and power.<p>
Klein's <i><a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/redirect.html?ie=UTF8&amp;location=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2FNo-Logo-Space-Choice-Jobs%2Fdp%2F0312421435%3Fie%3DUTF8%26s%3Dbooks%26qid%3D1197235238%26sr%3D8-2&amp;tag=socialistwork-20&amp;linkCode=ur2&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325" target="_blank">No Logo: No Space, No Choice, No Jobs</a> </i>became an indispensable book for the global justice movement.<p>
On this subject, she is also the author with Avi Lewis of an introduction to <i><a href="http://www.haymarketbooks.org/Merchant2/merchant.mv?Screen=PROD&amp;Store_Code=Haymarket&amp;Product_Code=LASPA" target="_blank">Sin Patr&oacute;n: Stories from Argentina's Worker-Run Factories</a>, </i>a book written by the lavaca collective that documents the rise of Argentina's remarkable movement, in the face of a catastrophic economic crisis, to occupy and reopen factories under the democratic control of workers themselves.<p>
Anthony Arnove is the author of <i><a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/redirect.html?ie=UTF8&location=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2FIraq-Withdrawal-American-Empire-Project%2Fdp%2F0805082727%2Fsr%3D1-2%2Fqid%3D1169579666%3Fie%3DUTF8%26s%3Dbooks&tag=socialistwork-20&linkCode=ur2&camp=1789&creative=9325" target="_blank">Iraq: The Logic of Withdrawal</a>, </i>a crucial book for antiwar activists, available in an updated paperback edition from the American Empire Project with a foreword by Howard Zinn.<p>
For more discussion of the issues raised in this interview, read the <i><a href="http://www.isreview.org" target="_blank">International Socialist Review</a></i>--see, for example, Joel Geier's <a href="http://www.isreview.org/issues/52/imperialcrisis.shtml" target="_blank">"Crisis of U.S. imperialism."</a>
</td></tr></table>
